Here's your code with proper sliding animation:
javascript<AnimatePresence>
  {category && (
    <motion.div
      initial={{ y: -50, opacity: 0 }}    // â† Changed from 0 to -50
      animate={{ y: 0, opacity: 1 }}
      exit={{ y: -50, opacity: 0 }}       // â† Changed from 0 to -50
      transition={{ duration: 0.4, ease: "easeOut" }}
      className=''
    >
      <div className='bg-[#D2863C]/20 text-[#d2863c] text-sm font-medium
        py-2 px-4 rounded-2xl flex gap-2 items-center w-fit'>
        <LuTag />
        <p> Category: {currentCategoryName}</p>
        <button onClick={() => setCategory("")}>
          <IoClose className='text-lg cursor-pointer hover:text-[#e4a260]' />
        </button>
      </div>
    </motion.div>
  )}
</AnimatePresence>

Understanding y values:

y: -50 â†’ 50 pixels above normal position (negative = up)
y: 0 â†’ Normal position (no offset)
y: 50 â†’ 50 pixels below normal position (positive = down)

You can adjust the number to control how far it slides:

y: -30 â†’ Subtle slide (30px from above)
y: -80 â†’ Dramatic slide (80px from above)
y: -100 â†’ Very dramatic slide (100px from above)


Quick Comparison:
CodeEffecty: 0 to y: 0âŒ No sliding, only fadey: -50 to y: 0âœ… Slides down from abovey: 50 to y: 0âœ… Slides up from below
Try changing it to -50 and you'll see the sliding animation! ğŸ¯so if i put it down thid paginated.map, it will calculate it height from that?9:24 PMGreat question! Let me explain how y positioning works in Framer Motion.
Short Answer: NO âŒ
The y value is always calculated from the element's natural position, not from where you place it in the code.

How y works:
Think of it like this:

The browser first figures out where the element should be on the page (its natural position)
Then Framer Motion offsets it by the y value
The y value is relative to that natural position, not to other elements


Example to understand:
javascript// Example 1: Tag at the TOP of the page
<div className='min-h-screen'>
  <AnimatePresence>
    {category && (
      <motion.div initial={{ y: -50, opacity: 0 }}>
        <div>Category Tag</div>
      </motion.div>
    )}
  </AnimatePresence>
  
  <div>Other content...</div>
</div>
Result: Tag slides down from 50px above its natural position at the top

javascript// Example 2: Tag at the BOTTOM of the page
<div className='min-h-screen'>
  <div>Other content...</div>
  
  {paginatedData.map(item => <ProductCard key={item.id} item={item} />)}
  
  <AnimatePresence>
    {category && (
      <motion.div initial={{ y: -50, opacity: 0 }}>
        <div>Category Tag</div>
      </motion.div>
    )}
  </AnimatePresence>
</div>
```
**Result:** Tag slides down from 50px above its natural position at the bottom

